  "prompt": "Can cataracts affect younger people? What are the most common causes of it?",
  "response": "Yes, cataracts can affect younger people, though they are more common in older adults. Here's some information about cataracts in younger individuals:\n\nCommon Causes of Cataracts in Younger People:\n\n1. Congenital causes:\n- Present at birth\n- Genetic disorders\n- Developmental issues\n\n2. Medical conditions:\n- Diabetes\n- Autoimmune disorders\n- Eye injuries or trauma\n- Prolonged steroid use\n\n3. Lifestyle and environmental factors:\n- Excessive UV light exposure\n- Smoking\n- Poor nutrition\n- Excessive alcohol consumption\n\n4. Rare genetic conditions:\n- Down syndrome\n- Marfan syndrome\n- Premature birth\n\n5. Other potential causes:\n- Radiation exposure\n- Some medications\n- Certain eye surgeries\n\nRisk Factors for Younger People:\n- Family history of early cataracts\n- Chronic health conditions\n- High-risk occupations with eye exposure\n- Repeated eye injuries\n\nWhile age-related cataracts typically develop after 60, some people can develop cataracts in their 40s or 50s. Early detection through regular eye exams is crucial for managing and treating cataracts effectively.",
